{"add":{"doc":{"id":"deb7358630a3238c29fd6cf01121fda2e16bdd1d1aaddcb468930fe7f54cdfa1","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/bb/Ramones_-_Ramones_cover.jpg/220px-Ramones_-_Ramones_cover.jpg","previous":[],"after":["The first wave of punk rock aimed to be aggressively modern, distancing itself from the bombast and sentimentality of early 1970s rock.[3] According to Ramones drummer Tommy Ramone, \"In its initial form, a lot of [1960s] stuff was innovative and exciting. Unfortunately, what happens is that people who could not hold a candle to the likes of Hendrix started noodling away. Soon you had endless solos that went nowhere. By 1973, I knew that what was needed was some pure, stripped down, no bullshit rock 'n' roll.\"[4] John Holmstrom, founding editor of Punk magazine, recalls feeling \"punk rock had to come along because the rock scene had become so tame that [acts] like Billy Joel and Simon and Garfunkel were being called rock and roll, when to me and other fans, rock and roll meant this wild and rebellious music.\"[5] In critic Robert Christgau's description, \"It was also a subculture that scornfully rejected the political idealism and Californian flower-power silliness of hippie myth.\"[6]"]}}}